node.text:
WIC is increasing the fruits and vegetables in the WIC food package this summer! Check your local WIC office, since it varies by location. ⁠
⁠
WIC - the supplemental nutrition program for women, infants, and children in the US is an evidence-based protein. It’s had decades of beneficial health outcomes for woman, infants, and children. ⁠
⁠
Why should you care? ⁠
⁠
If you qualify, it can help you get more fruits, vegetables, whole grains, dairy, etc. It can help you feed your family and make your food budget stretch. And many farmer’s markets double WIC vouchers (look into it in your area). ⁠
⁠
If you don’t qualify, you should know that stigma against the program and against people with a low income is one reason people don’t participate. Even though their families would be healthier with it, they are treated so poorly by other people in stores and in public, that they stop participating. Don’t be those people. ⁠
⁠⁠
If we want to improve the nutrition of ourselves and fellow parents and children, it's smart to learn how to use all the food opportunities that are available - like WIC. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If you are using WIC, you might find our new Affordable Flavors meal plan to be helpful (link in bio). WIC items are marked on the shopping lists. Plus, if it's not in your budget, you can get it free. Or if you want to support a family getting it, you can donate to make it free for someone else.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I've benefited from WIC. Have you?⁠⁠
#kidseatincolor⁠⁠

node.text:
Can kids eat too much fruit? If your child won't eat veggies, make sure and fill in some of the nutritional gaps with fruit (not fruit juice) while they are learning to like veggies. Just because fruit is sweet doesn't mean that it is the same as an added-sugar dessert. Fruit is loaded with vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, and fiber. When I serve fruit, I let my kids eat their fill (unless I run out 😉). ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Fruit juice is NOT a whole fruit. I recommend serving water and milk as normal beverages and serving juice only occasionally and trying to delay juice until after the age of 2. If you choose to serve juice regularly, keep it to 4 oz of fruit juice or less per day. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
🥦✨Need help getting your kids to eat veggies? You can get my FREE NEW child feeding guide/picky eater guide in my bio @kids.eat.in.color.✨🥦⁠⁠

"I'm eating these foods feel my strongest." "I'm eating these foods because have XYZ and these foods will help my body stay strong."'.

node.text:
If you're an adult, you're free to do what you want with your body. Maybe you've decided to lose weight. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
There are 2 ways you can communicate this to your child.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
First, you can say something like this common narrative "Fat makes me unhealthy and so I'm trying to lose weight so that I can be healthy."⁠⁠
⁠⁠
It's a really common message, so I don't blame anyone for having this immediately pop up into their minds. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The thing is, when we say this to kids, we teach them that losing weight makes you healthy (not necessarily true), fat is bad, there's something wrong with someone who is fat. These sorts of messages are absolutely unhelpful and can even predispose kids to eating disorders (and weight stigma).⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Maybe that doesn't sit well...and you want something else to say.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
You can say something like "The doctor showed me I have high blood pressure. That is telling me that my body is sick and it needs help. The things that will help me are eating more fruits and vegetables and also moving around every day."⁠⁠
⁠⁠
When you say something like this, you show your child that food is important, movement is important, your health is important. Doing something to protect your health is important. It's also a movement away from diet culture and a movement toward focusing on true health. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
And if you started with the first, but want to try the second? Do it! Tell your child you've changed your focus and why. That will be just as helpful to them. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Have you ever had one of these conversations with your child? ⁠⁠
#kidseatincolor⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁠⁠

node.text:
At the end, we want our kids to be able to eat good food and eat the right amount of food for their body. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Pushing kids to finish their plate makes mealtime a lot more stressful in the short term. It also makes it harder for kids to listen to whether they are hungry or full. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Knowing if you are hungry or full is a skill. Not all kids do a great job at it right away (although most do). It's a skill we need to keep teaching kids over time. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If you're struggling with mealtime battles, the free picky eater guide in our bio is a great place to start. ⁠⁠
#kidseatincolor⁠⁠

node.text:
I had just finished describing to another mom how delighted I was when my 6-month-old grabbed the spoon out of my hand and fed himself the puree... ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Then it happened... ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
"Well WE decided to do baby led weaning. It was the right decision for us, it was so great...blah...blah..." ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Deflated, I stopped hearing the rest of her story. I could feel the judgement past the words that seemed nonjudgemental. As a brand new mom, the people who made me feel the absolute worst during that first year were the people doing baby led weaning. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Fun fact, I was following evidence-based responsive feeding practices for feeding my kid. He was fine.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
There are a lot of great things about baby led weaning. I didn't do it (I did "whatever I want" weaning...but that's another post), but I don't have anything against the method. I have everything against how it can be presented and how that presentation makes other people feel. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
There are lots of ways to wean a baby and to help get them the nutrition and experience they need to be healthy long term. Each family's situation is unique. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
To get past the nonjudgemental nature of things, we really have to work extra hard to listen to other people's stories. That helps us accept that different family's have different BESTs for them. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I built @kids.eat.in.color to be that safe place, where what's best for your family IS the best. We welcome with open arms the parents who choose to do purees. The parents who choose to do what felt right to them because of cost, time, family structure, mental health or more - whatever that looked like. The parents who did BLW, but still got a picky toddler. The parents who had to give up BLW because their infant couldn't do it. The parents who loves BLW.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Whatever weaning looks like for you, we're here for you.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Have you ever felt judged by how you weaned? ⁠⁠
#kidseatincolor⁠⁠

node.text:
You'll never see me bash ketchup. Why? It helps kids eat tons of different foods - if they are a ketchup kid. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
In fact, I wish my kid's ketchup phase was longer. He would eat ANYTHING with ketchup on it! Now he's gone moderate on ketchup. 🤷‍♀️ (PS - why I'm never that concerned about a kid eating tons of ketchup, often they grow out of it).⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The amazing thing about colorful fruits and veggies is that they have compounds inside them that give them their color. Those compounds do things in our bodies to protect us from disease long term. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Color literally does something in our bodies. 🌈 It's worth keeping on helping our kids learn to eat colorful foods. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If you need help, BetterBites, our course for families of picky eaters is coming up! Link in bio for waitlist. ⁠⁠
#kidseatincolor⁠⁠

Try this! Make it a game.

Of your child is struggling with drinking enough, a game like this can be a fun way to bring more attention to it.

node.text:
“Mommy, Josie said chocolate is bad for you, but it just does a few things in your body, right?” M asked me this last year. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If I could teach my kids just ONE thing about nutrition, it would be that foods do different things and different amounts of things in our bodies. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
As a deep thinking person, and ever learning nutrition professional, I know a lot. I especially know a lot about the nuance. The gray areas. The part where food isn’t black and white. The part where bad for me is good for you. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
And I won’t raise my kids thinking some foods are categorically bad and others are categorically good...giving them kindling to burn down some other kid’s culture, self-worth, or safety. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I also don’t want to raise them thinking what we eat doesn’t matter and they shouldn’t care about what they eat. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
So that time we talked about chocolate when he was five, I told him it did a few things in his body... and other foods that he likes, like carrots, do a whole bunch of things. We learned about some of the things. When the prevailing cultural opinion that foods are good or bad, healthy or unhealthy hot him in the face at the ripe age of SIX, guess what... he had some questions about the information shoved in his face. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Is chocolate really bad? Or does it just do a few things in our body? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
You may have seen this post before... but I post it from time to time, because it’s just that important for us to remember that giving kids information about foods is more powerful than giving them labels. The will eventually run into a situation where the labels fail or do harm. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁠If you need help with picky eating, the free picky eater guide is in my bio - and if you don’t have a picky eater, but you want to include more veggies - my free shopping list is also in my bio ⁠@kids.eat.in.color⁠. 😘⁠⁠
#kidseatincolor⁣⠀⁠⁠
